clegg@ripco.com (Robert Zubek) writes:

>Forgive me, if that has been mentioned here before, but I'm new to this 
>group, and to public key cryptography as well.  The problem is,
>I have been browsing thru some text files about RSA, when I came across this:
>(edited for clarity)

>    m=(p-1)(q-1)=40
>    Pick E and d so that Ed = 1 mod (m):
>                         E = 3, d = 27

>The "mod" used above does not seem to be the "ordinary" modulus function, 
>sine 1 mod 40 (or 1 % 40, if you prefer) = 1, and not 81.  What is it then?

I think that should be Ed mod m =1 which gives 81 mod 40 = 1.
Not that 40 makes a great modulus. Also E must be relatively prime to m 
for E^-1 to be defined.

